## 1. Objective

The aim of this experiment is to characterise standing-wave resonance in a
finite air column and to use those resonances to (i) measure the speed of
sound in air at room temperature, (ii) quantify the *end-effect* correction
predicted by the empirical formula \(L_{\mathrm{eff}}=L+0.3\,d\), and (iii)
contrast the harmonic structure of an open tube with that of a closed tube.

The study addresses the four explicit questions raised in the PASCO
manual (Experiments 1 and 2) and the *Further Investigation* prompts that
ask for the relation between adjacent resonance positions, the harmonic
ratio between open and closed tubes, and the physical reason that a
closed tube only supports odd harmonics. We adopt the manual's reference
value \(v_{\mathrm{ref}}=340\ \text{m/s}\) as ground truth.

## 2. Method

### 2.1 Apparatus and Driving Signal

A 120 cm transparent tube of inner diameter
\(d={{ "%.1f"|format(params.tube_diameter_cm) }}\ \text{cm}\) was modelled
on a uniform spatial grid of {{ params.n_nodes }} interior nodes.
The speaker end (x = 0) is acoustically open: it carries a free Neumann
boundary \(\partial_{x} u\!\mid_{0}=0\) on top of which a sinusoidal
*velocity* soft-source injects energy at amplitude
\(A={{ "%.2f"|format(params.A_drive_mm) }}\ \text{mm}\), faithfully
modelling a piston-type loudspeaker driving an open tube.
The far end of the tube switches between the *closed* boundary
\(u(L,t)=0\) (rigid piston) and the *open* boundary
\(\partial_{x} u\!\mid_{L}=0\) (free reflection), reproducing the two
configurations described in the manual.

### 2.2 Mathematical Model

Sound waves were treated as small longitudinal displacements obeying
the damped 1-D wave equation
\[
\frac{\partial^{2} u}{\partial t^{2}} \;=\; c^{2}\,\frac{\partial^{2} u}{\partial x^{2}}
   \;-\; 2\gamma\,\frac{\partial u}{\partial t},
\qquad x\in[0,L],
\]
with damping coefficient
\(\gamma={{ "%.2f"|format(params.gamma) }}\ \text{s}^{-1}\)
representing the cumulative effect of viscous and thermal losses.
Resonance is expected when the driver frequency satisfies
\[
\text{(closed)} \quad L+0.3\,d=\frac{(2n-1)\,\lambda}{4}, \qquad
\text{(open)}\quad L+0.6\,d=\frac{n\,\lambda}{2},
\quad \lambda = c/f,
\]
where the additional \(0.3\,d\) (or \(0.6\,d\)) is the empirical
*end-effect*. Equation (3) of the manual,
\(L=\tfrac{1}{4}(v/f)\), implies that plotting \(L\) against \(1/f\)
yields a straight line of slope \(v/4\) and a non-zero y-intercept
\(L_{0}=-0.3\,d\).

### 2.3 Numerical Procedure

Each spatial grid was advanced with a second-order leapfrog finite
difference scheme,
\[
u_{i}^{\,n+1} = 2u_{i}^{\,n} - u_{i}^{\,n-1}
   + \!\left(\frac{c\,\Delta t}{h}\right)^{\!2}
       \!\big(u_{i+1}^{\,n}-2u_{i}^{\,n}+u_{i-1}^{\,n}\big)
   - 2\gamma\,\Delta t\big(u_{i}^{\,n}-u_{i}^{\,n-1}\big).
\]
The time step \(\Delta t\) was chosen 15% below the CFL limit
\(\Delta t<h/c\) to ensure stability. After
\(t_{w}={{ "%.1f"|format(params.t_warmup) }}\ \text{s}\) of warm-up
the steady-state peak amplitude
\(\hat u(L,f)=\max_{x\in(0,L)}|u(x,t)|\) was averaged over a
\(t_{m}={{ "%.1f"|format(params.t_measure) }}\ \text{s}\) measurement
window.

### 2.4 Sweeps Performed

A short Python harness then ran four sweeps and stored every output to
the report directory:

1. Frequency sweep at the user-selected length
   \(L_{u}={{ "%.1f"|format(params.L_user_cm) }}\ \text{cm}\),
   \({{ params.mode_user }}\) configuration.
2. Closed-tube fundamental search at every length in
   \(\{40,50,60,70,80,90,100,110\}\ \text{cm}\) (Experiment 1 of the manual).
3. Length sweep at fixed frequency
   \(f_{0}={{ "%.0f"|format(f_fixed_for_length_sweep_Hz) }}\ \text{Hz}\)
   (Further Investigation).
4. Open vs. closed spectrum at the user length (Experiment 2 of the manual).

