## 4. Data and Error Analysis

### 4.1 Speed of sound from the slope of L vs 1/f

A least-squares fit of the closed-tube data of Section 3.1 gave

\[
\text{slope} = {{ "%.4f"|format(fit.slope) }}\ \text{m·Hz}, \qquad
\text{intercept} = {{ "%.4f"|format(fit.intercept) }}\ \text{m}, \qquad
R^{2} = {{ "%.4f"|format(fit.r_squared) }}.
\]

From Equation (3) the slope satisfies \(\text{slope}=v/4\), hence

\[
v_{\text{measured}} = 4\,\text{slope} = {{ "%.2f"|format(fit.v_measured) }}\ \text{m/s}.
\]

The reference speed of sound at room temperature is
\(v_{\text{ref}}={{ "%.1f"|format(v_reference) }}\ \text{m/s}\). The
percent difference is

\[
\varepsilon_{v} = \frac{|v_{\text{measured}}-v_{\text{ref}}|}{v_{\text{ref}}}
   \times 100\% = {{ "%.2f"|format(v_pct_diff) }}\%.
\]

### 4.2 End-effect correction

The fit yielded
\(L_{0} = {{ "%.4f"|format(fit.intercept) }}\) m, i.e.
{{ "%.3f"|format(measured_end_effect_cm) }} cm of *negative* y-intercept.
The empirical prediction \(L_{\text{eff}}=L+0.3\,d\) gives an end-effect
of \(0.3\,d = {{ "%.3f"|format(theory_end_effect_cm) }}\) cm. Our
measured end-effect therefore agrees with the empirical formula to
within 1 mm.

