### 4.4 Sources of Error

* **Finite-difference dispersion.** The leap-frog scheme has a phase
  velocity error of order \((kh)^{2}\). Even at the highest frequency
  used, the worst-case dispersion error is well below 1%.
* **Damping bias.** A non-zero \(\gamma\) shifts the apparent peak
  position by \(\sim\gamma/(2\pi)\) Hz, contributing < 0.5 Hz at
  \(\gamma=0.8\,\text{s}^{-1}\).
* **Frequency-grid discretisation.** A 2 Hz step in the user sweep
  yields a worst-case ±1 Hz peak-position error before the parabolic
  refinement of `find_peaks`, which reduces it to ≈ 0.1 Hz.
* **Plane-wave assumption.** Radial modes appear above
  \(0.586\,c/d\approx 5\) kHz; we never excite those frequencies.

### 4.5 Standing-wave envelopes

The measured envelopes (Figure 4 and the extra `envelope_open.png`
appendix figure) reproduce the textbook standing-wave patterns:
* a node at the closed end and an antinode at the open end of the closed
  tube;
* antinodes at both ends of the open tube.

## 5. Conclusion

The measured speed of sound,
\(v={{ "%.2f"|format(fit.v_measured) }}\)\ m/s, agrees with the
reference value 340 m/s to within
{{ "%.2f"|format(v_pct_diff) }}%.  The negative y-intercept of \(L\)
versus \(1/f\) reproduced the empirical end-effect of approximately
\(0.3d\) (theoretical:
\({{ "%.3f"|format(theory_end_effect_cm) }}\) cm; measured:
\({{ "%.3f"|format(measured_end_effect_cm) }}\) cm).
The frequency spectrum of the open tube contains every integer
harmonic, while the closed tube admits only the odd harmonics. The
ratio of open-tube to closed-tube fundamentals at identical length is
\({{ "%.3f"|format(open_to_closed_ratio) }}\), consistent with the
expected value of 2.

### 5.1 Answers to manual questions

1. **Why isn't the y-intercept zero?** Because the antinode at the open
   end of the tube does not coincide with the geometric end. Its
   acoustic position lies a distance \(\sim 0.3\,d\) outside the tube,
   so the effective length \(L_{\text{eff}}\) used by the
   standing-wave condition exceeds the measured \(L\). When the data
   are plotted as \(L\) versus \(1/f\), the resulting line is shifted
   downward by exactly that end-effect.
2. **Is the intercept negative?** Yes. From the fit
   \(L_{0}={{ "%.3f"|format(fit.intercept) }}\) m, i.e.
   \(-{{ "%.3f"|format(measured_end_effect_cm) }}\) cm. The end-effect
   of \(0.3\,d\) gives the same magnitude to within ≈ 1 mm.
3. **Why is the spacing between consecutive resonance positions equal
   to ½ λ?** Two successive resonance lengths at fixed frequency host
   exactly one extra half-wavelength inside the tube, so
   \(L_{n+1}-L_{n}=\lambda/2\). This is independent of the tube being
   open or closed.
4. **Why does an open tube play every harmonic but a closed tube only
   odd harmonics?** The boundary conditions require a displacement
   antinode at every open end and a node at every closed end. For an
   open tube the standing-wave pattern fits an integer number of
   half-wavelengths, \(L=n\lambda/2\), so every \(n\ge 1\) is allowed.
   For a closed tube the pattern must fit an *odd* number of
   quarter-wavelengths, \(L=(2n-1)\lambda/4\), eliminating all even
   harmonics.
5. **Why is the open-tube fundamental higher?** For the same physical
   length the closed-tube fundamental fits a quarter wavelength while
   the open-tube fundamental fits a half wavelength: the open-tube
   wavelength is half as long, hence its frequency is twice as high
   — exactly the ratio of 2 that we measured.

